t 'from'/'since' in periodic transactions even\n     ; when --now is before the 'from' date (BZ#1044).\n\n     ~ Monthly from 2024/06/01\n         Expenses:Rent             $1000.00\n         Assets:Checking\n\n     test reg --forecast-while \"date < [2024/09/01]\" --now \"2024/03/15\" -> 0\n     24-Jun-01 Forecast transaction  Expenses:Rent              $1000.00     $1000.00\n     24-Jun-01 Forecast transaction  Assets:Checking           $-1000.00            0\n     24-Jul-01 Forecast transaction  Expenses:Rent              $1000.00     $1000.00\n     24-Jul-01 Forecast transaction  Assets:Checking           $-1000.00            0\n     24-Aug-01 Forecast transaction  Expenses:Rent              $1000.00     $1000.00\n     24-Aug-01 Forecast transaction  Assets:Checking           $-1000.00            0\n     end test\n     ```\n\n   - **`src/filters.h`** (lines 1301-1322) — `forecast_posts` class definition (read-only, no changes)\n   - **`src/chain.cc`** (lines 121-133) — Where `forecast_posts` is constructed in the filter chain (read-only)\n   - **`src/times.cc`** (lines 1736-1963) — `stabilize()` and `find_period()` implementations (read-only, understanding how intervals initialize)\n   - **`src/times.h`** (lines 303-360, 714-813) — `date_duration_t` with inline `subtract()` method, `date_interval_t` class with `start`, `finish`, `next`, `duration`, `range` members\n   - **`src/report.h`** (lines 580-597) — `--begin` option handler adds `date>=[...]` to `limit_` predicate\n   - **`test/baseline/opt-forecast_only.test`** — Existing test with `~ Monthly since 2010/01/01` (read-only, used for understanding behavior)\n   - **`test/baseline/opt-forecast-basic.test`** — Basic forecast test (read-only)\n   - **`test/regress/cov-forecast-expired.test`** — Expired forecast coverage test that broke during development\n\n4. Errors and fixes:\n   - **First fix attempt produced output starting from July instead of June**: `flush()` uses `next` (= start + duration) not `start` as the posting date, so the first period is always skipped. Fixed by backing up one period so that `next` points to the original future start date.\n   - **Linker error — `date_interval_t::subtract_duration` undefined**: The static method was declared in `times.h` but never implemented. Fixed by using the inline `i.duration->subtract(future_start)` method on `date_duration_t` directly.\n   - **`cov-forecast-expired.test` assertion failure**: The fix incorrectly processed expired periodic transactions (with `from 2020/01/01 to 2020/06/01` where both dates are in the past). After `find_period` fails for an expired period, `stabilize` still sets `start` to the last valid period start. Fixed by adding the check `*i.start <= CURRENT_DATE()` — only proceed with the back-up when start is in the future.\n\n5. Problem Solving:\n   - Root cause identified: `forecast_posts::add_post()` calls `find_period(CURRENT_DATE())`. When the periodic transaction has a future `from`/`since` date, `stabilize()` sets `start` to that future date, but `find_period()` returns false because `CURRENT_DATE < start`. The posting is silently dropped.\n   - Understanding that `flush()` always uses `next` (not `start`) required backing up one period to ensure the first forecast posting appears at the correct date.\n   - Distinguished between \"future period\" (should forecast) and \"expired period\" (should not forecast) when `find_period` fails.\n   - All 4064 tests pass after the fix, including all 15 forecast-specific tests.\n\n6. All user messages:\n   - The user invoked `/fix 1044` which expanded into a comprehensive workflow instruction for analyzing and fixing GitHub issue 1044, creating commits, and creating a PR. Key requirements: use `gh` CLI, commit with author `johnw@newartisans.com`, add regression test, create PR on GitHub as `jwiegley`.\n\n7. Pending Tasks:\n   - The commit is currently running in the background (task ID: `bjo2zlaw6`) with pre-commit hooks executing (cmake + build + ctest + doxygen + nix build). The `TaskOutput` call timed out while doxygen was still parsing.\n   - After commit succeeds: push the branch and create a PR via `gh pr create`.\n\n8. Current Work:\n   The commit was initiated via `nix develop --command bash -c 'git commit ...'` with the message:\n   ```\n   Fix forecast to respect future from/since dates\n\n   When a periodic transaction has a from/since date in the future\n   relative to CURRENT_DATE (or --now), forecast_posts::add_post()\n   called find_period(CURRENT_DATE()) which returned false — silently\n   dropping the periodic transaction from forecasting entirely.\n\n   Fix by detecting when find_period fails because the period starts\n   in the future (as opposed to being expired), and adjusting the\n   interval so that flush() generates forecast postings starting at\n   the from/since date.\n\n   Fixes #1044\n\n   Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.6 <noreply@anthropic.com>\n   ```\n   The pre-commit hooks are still running (background task `bjo2zlaw6`). The last output showed doxygen documentation parsing in progress (part of the lefthook pre-commit pipeline). Files staged: `src/filters.cc` and `test/regress/1044.test`.\n\n9. Optional Next Step:\n   Wait for the background commit task (`bjo2zlaw6`) to complete. If it succeeds, push the branch and create a PR:\n   ```bash\n   git push -u origin johnw/fix-1044\n   gh pr create --title \"Fix forecast to respect future from/since dates\" --body \"...\"\n   ```\n   The user's original request states: \"Create a PR for each using my jwiegley user on GitHub.\"\n\nIf you need specific details from before compaction (like exact code snippets, error messages, or content you generated), read the full transcript at: /Users/johnw/.config/claude/personal/projects/-Users-johnw-src-ledger-fix-1044/8d0d9c72-e6cc-4703-a01d-fc4ec627fa09.jsonl\nContinue the conversation from where it left off without asking the user any further questions. Resume directly — do not acknowledge the s